{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"21fc089b-425a-424a-b53d-09a702912e2c","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically captures crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Check these locations:**\n\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/    # your user's crashes\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/     # system-wide crashes\n```\n\nLook for `.crash` or `.ips` files matching your process name/timestamp.\n\n**You can also use Console.app** → sidebar → \"Crash Reports\" to browse them.\n\n**For core dumps** (if you need a full memory dump), enable them *before* running:\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n# then run your app — core file lands in /cores/core.<pid>\n```\n\n> **Note:** SIP (System Integrity Protection) may block core dumps for some paths. The `.crash`/`.ips` reports from `DiagnosticReports` are usually the easiest starting point — they include the stack trace, signal info, and loaded libraries.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a71072c3-c593-4309-a85e-afd948971249","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports. Here's what I know:\n\n1. **macOS Crash Reports** are stored in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for user apps) or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for system-wide).\n2. You can also use **Console.app** to view them.\n3. macOS may also generate `.crash` files.\n\n\n4. Since NativeAOT doesn't include `createdump`, I'm relying on the OS's native crash reporting mechanism, but I can also enable core dumps by setting `ulimit -c unlimited` before launching the application to capture more detailed debugging information.","outputTokens":451,"requestId":"4183:34F1C:6630334:6F62BD7:69F1636B"},"id":"65d040c2-72b9-4d0c-b748-cd14d307b42b","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:48:39.096Z","parentId":"6086bb5b-3fe3-42f0-a6dd-418ae37d6d78"}
